<h3>
    Part 2: Particle Motion in Transverse and Longitudinal Waves
</h3>

<p class="definition" data-word = 'oscillate'>
    Harmonic Motion;
    When something oscillates, it moves then returns to its original spot.
    We represent oscillation with a double-headed arrow.
</p>

<p class="definition" data-word = 'Mechanical Wave'>
    A mechanical wave allows energy to move through a moving oscillation.
    When a mechanical wave passes through some particles,
    the oscillate, but they do not travel.
</p>

<p class="definition" data-word = 'Transverse Mechanical Wave'>
    When a transverse mechanical wave comes through,
    every particle oscillates in a direction <strong>perpendicular</strong> to the motion of the wave.
</p>


<p class="definition" data-wird = 'Longitudinal Mechanical Wave'>
    When a longitudinal wave comes through,
    every particle oscillates in a direction <strong>parallel</strong> to the motion of the wave.
</p>

